  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential prison sentences\n- Up to 20 years imprisonment per offense\n- Potentially longer sentences if connected to other serious crimes\n\n2. Financial penalties\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Often up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved\n\n3. Asset forfeiture\n- Government can seize assets related to the laundering activity\n- May include money, property, and other valuable assets\n\n4. Additional consequences\n- Criminal record\n- Potential loss of professional licenses\n- Difficulty securing future employment\n- Immigration consequences for non-citizens\n\n5. Civil penalties\n- Potential additional monetary sanctions\n- Separate from criminal prosecution\n\nThe specific penalties depend on factors like:\n- Amount of money laundered\n- Specific circumstances of the offense\n- Prior criminal history\n- Whether the laundering involved other criminal activities\n\nProsecution typically occurs under statutes like:\n- The Bank Secrecy Act\n- Money Laundering Control Act\n- Proceeds of Crime Act\n\nActual sentencing can vary based on individual case details and prosecution strategies.",
